The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Multiple injuries plague EB

 - PREMIER DIVISION TIE vs MD. SPORTING

A STAFF REPORTER

 Mohammedan Sportings foreign recruits ? (from left) Okonji Patrick, Erick and Suley Musah ? share a light moment during practice on Friday. Picture by Gautam Bose 

Calcutta: These are troubled times for East Bengal and even the fallen giants, Mohammedan Sporting, are eyeing three points when they meet Subhas Bhowmicks side in a CFL Premier Division match at the Salt Lake Stadium on Saturday. 

To add to Bhowmicks woes, East Bengal are saddled with multiple injuries. 

I.M. Vijayan, Rajat Ghosh Dastidar, Naseem Akhtar and Chandan Das are on the list. M. Suresh and Sasthi Duley are also not 100 per cent fit and may not take the field on Saturday. 

East Bengal will also miss the services of Dipankar Roy, out of station playing office matches. The red-and-golds are set to field few new faces to test their bench strength. 

We are focusing on the Federation Cup now and so we will take this as the preparation, assistant coach Bikash Panji said after the days practice session. 

East Bengal, with 22 points from 10 outings, have no chance of retaining the title. They are eight points behind league leaders Mohun Bagan. 

Mohammedan Sporting , who are on 13 points from nine ties will look to strengthen their position. All matches are vital for us now, coach Biswajit Bhattacharya said. 

The black-and-whites will be boosted when new Ghanaian recruit Patrick D Souza takes the field alongside countrymate Suley Musah. It was announced on behalf of the club that the players will given Rs 1 lakh in cash if they win on Saturday. But Mohammedan Sporting also have injury problems. Abdul Kadir is ruled out with malaria. 

Meanwhile, Allahabad Bank will give East Bengal a financial assistance of Rs 15 lakh for the upcoming National Football League. 




